{"updated_at": "2012-11-13T19:16:34Z", "repo": "rails", "created_at": "2012-11-13T19:16:34Z", "owner": "rails", "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rails/rails/issues/comments/10338866", "id": 10338866, "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/rails/rails/issues/8124", "issue_id": 8124, "user": {"repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/repos", "type": "User", "html_url": "https://github.com/alexaandru", "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/starred{/owner}{/repo}", "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/subscriptions", "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/following{/other_user}", "gravatar_id": "1b3eba0eda442464cb4de44336a9744c", "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/orgs", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru", "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/gists{/gist_id}", "avatar_url": "https://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1b3eba0eda442464cb4de44336a9744c?d=https%3A%2F%2Fidenticons.github.com%2Fb2e8e0c84b611b24e270244b27a6d28b.png", "id": 85237, "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/events{/privacy}", "login": "alexaandru", "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/received_events", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/alexaandru/followers"}, "body": "Quoting from: http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#page-54\r\n\r\n> The HEAD method is identical to GET except that the server MUST NOT\r\n> return a message-body in the response.\r\n\r\nI don't see anything unclear there, that could lead to a philosophical debate. \"MUST NOT\" MUST (pun not intended) be interpreted as per: http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2119 which means:\r\n\r\n> MUST NOT -  This phrase, or the phrase \"SHALL NOT\", mean that the\r\n> definition is an absolute prohibition of the specification.\r\n\r\nIf someone expects a body, they should not use a HTTP verb that prevents returning a body in the first place.", "_id": {"$oid": "5237f5cbbd3543c15100acc4"}, "html_url": "https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/8124#issuecomment-10338866"}
